[Guinea's investment agency said the economy showed signs of recovery from the Ebola outbreak with the rapid growth of small businesses in the West African nation...more]

19 Aug 2015 Liberia: Ivorian border closure worrisome
http://allafrica.com/stories/201508191008.html
[The Mano River Union Secretariat has warned that the border closure between Liberia, Guinea and the Ivory Coast is worrisome because it undermines regional integration, trade, peace and security as well as impedes efforts to conduct rigorous surveillance for Ebola virus disease [EVD] outbreaks across borders. The body of Mano River Union is appealing to the government of Ivory Coast to reopen its frontiers with both countries...more]

23 Aug 2015 Liberia [Partnership for Research on Ebola Vaccines in Liberia (PREVAIL)]: With many Ebola survivors ailing, doctors evaluate situation
http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/A/AF_EBOLA_SICK_SURVIVORS?SITE=AP&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT&CTIME=2015-08-23-09-07-14
[Lingering health problems afflicting many of the roughly 13 000 Ebola survivors have galvanized global and local health officials to find out how widespread the ailments are, and how to remedy them. The World Health Organization calls it an emergency within an emergency. Many of the survivors have vision and hearing issues. Others experience physical and emotional pains, fatigue and other problems.

"If we can find out this kind of information, hopefully we can help other Ebola survivors in the future," Dr. Zan Yeong, an eye specialist involved in a study of health problems in survivors in Liberia, told The Associated Press. About 7500 people will enroll -- 1500 Ebola survivors and 6000 of their close contacts -- and will be monitored over a 5-year period in the study launched by Partnership for Research on Ebola Vaccines in Liberia, or PREVAIL. ...more]

19 Aug 2015 Nigeria, Sierra Leone: NFF [Nigeria Football Federation] ready to host CIV [Cote d'Ivoire], Sierra Leone AFCON [Africa Cup of Nations] clash in Nigeria
http://saharareporters.com/2015/08/19/ebola-alert-nff-ready-host-civ-sierra-leone-afcon-clash-nigeria
[Nigeria will host the 2017 Africa Cup of Nations qualifying match between the reigning African champions, Cote d'Ivoire, and the Leone Stars of Sierra Leone, the Nigeria Football Federation [NFF] announced on Wednesday [19 Aug 2015]. ... It will be recalled that since the Ebola virus pandemic that ravaged some West African countries last year [2014], the Confederation of African Football had compelled Guinea, Liberia, and Sierra Leone to find alternative venues for home matches. These countries have played their home matches in countries like Ghana, Morocco, Cameroon, Cote d'Ivoire, and Mali. ...more]

21 Aug 2015 Sierra Leone: Teen's killing highlights crime wave in Ebola-hit Sierra Leone
http://www.timeslive.co.za/africa/2015/08/21/Teens-killing-highlights-crime-wave-in-Ebola-hit-Sierra-Leone
[There has been a rise in violent crime in Sierra Leone attributed by authorities to the disruption of law enforcement by the year-old Ebola virus disease (EVD) outbreak.]

21 Aug 2015 Sierra Leone: An impoverished church is coping with aftermath of Ebola epidemic
http://www.zenit.org/en/articles/sierra-leone-an-impoverished-church-is-coping-with-aftermath-of-ebola-epidemic?utm_source=feedburner&utm_medium=feed&utm_campaign=Feed%3A+zenit%2Fenglish+%28ZENIT+English%29
[The Ebola epidemic may be largely contained, but the suffering it caused continues. Such is the case in one of the countries at the epidemic's epicenter, Sierra Leone, where, in the words of a leading Church official, "our biggest sorrow is the aftermath of Ebola." Today, Bishop Henry Aruna of Makeni told international Catholic charity Aid to the Church in Need that the church is on the forefront of caring for the orphans and others needing continued special care. ...more]

21 Aug 2015 Sierra Leone manhunt for fleeing Ebola suspects
http://en.starafrica.com/news/sleone-manhunt-for-fleeing-ebola-suspects.html
[The authorities in Sierra Leone have mounted a manhunt for 7 "high risk" Ebola suspects who are reportedly on the run, sources revealed on Fri [21 Aug 2015]. The incident is said to have happened in the east of Freetown, and search teams have been sent around the city. ... For the last 12 days there has been no new case of the disease. The only patient with the viral disease currently in the country is expected to be discharged on Mon [24 Aug 2015]. On Sun [23 Aug 2015], 43 people in holding centers in the north of the country are due for release.]

21 Aug 2015 Sierra Leone: NERC CEO orders funeral homes closed
http://allafrica.com/stories/201508230034.html
[Chief Executive Officer of the National Ebola Response Center (NERC), Retired Major Alfred Palo Conteh, has ordered the closure of funeral homes for storage of corpses after 20 Aug 2015. The funeral homes can still sell coffins and carry on administrative duties, however.

According to Conteh, staff of funeral homes will be incorporated into the existing burial teams to ensure compliance and successful implementation of the amended policy, while the Connaught Hospital mortuary will operate as storage for repatriated and medico-legal corpses, subject to the directives from the Chief Medical Officer and the pathologist. Conteh also said families in the Western Area will be offered the chance to negotiate safe and dignified burials at a cemetery of their choice within the Western Area only, and that it will cost SLL 25 000 [USD 5.38]. ...more]

20 Aug 2015 USA (New York): Doctors in New York have ruled out Ebola in suspected patient returned from Guinea
http://news.sky.com/story/1538423/doctors-rule-out-ebola-for-new-york-patient
[The person was taken to [Bellevue] hospital with symptoms associated with Ebola after a trip to [West] Africa, but doctors have now ruled that out.]

22 Aug 2015: Ebola diaries--Psychological toll to endure
http://www.who.int/features/2015/ebola-diaries-mulemba/en/
[A WHO [World Health Organization] logistician, Francis Mulemba, was 1st deployed to West Africa in March 2014 to respond to the 5th Ebola outbreak in his career. He took care of logistic and administrative tasks in Gueckedou, Guinea, the epicenter of the epidemic. Five months later, he was sent to Monrovia, Liberia to support training of the national burial teams. He said that the situation in Liberia was unlike any other Ebola outbreak he had experienced before. ...more]

Non-governmental organizations
---------------------
11 Aug 2015: Using real-time data to improve emergency response
http://www.ifrc.org/en/news-and-media/news-stories/africa/liberia/using-real-time-data-to-improve-emergency-response-68958/
[The Ebola outbreak in West Africa has been no exception in terms of logistical challenges, but it has nevertheless proven to be an opportunity for the Red Cross to pioneer an efficient method of data collection: Rapid Mobile Phone Based surveys, or RAMP. Combining this innovation with Red Cross's beneficiary communications approach -- dialogue with affected communities -- enabled Red Cross teams to rapidly inform and evaluate programming in the critical 1st days. ...more]

19 Aug 2015: Engaging communities on Ebola is about being able to re-mix the message http://www.ifrc.org/en/news-and-media/news-stories/africa/sierra-leone/engaging-communities-about-ebola-is-about-being-able-to-re-mix-the-message--69232/#sthash.w0wjkwKo.dpuf
["ABC: avoid body contact," "No touch" and "Ebola is real" became mantras to chant and print across Sierra Leone as the country continues to battle the unprecedented Ebola outbreak. Catchy and simple, communities have latched onto these snappy sayings and, for the most part, live by them. Education through social mobilization led to behavior change. Case rates tumbled.

Over 3000 Red Cross volunteers engaged in the Ebola emergency response have been central to binding communities to the words that will protect them from Ebola. The Sierra Leone Red Cross Society [SLRCS] and the International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies (IFRC) have carried out psychosocial support, contact tracing, safe and dignified burials, case management and social mobilization in Ebola affected communities. All 5 interventions have contributed to reigning in the outbreak. But it is dangerous to think that Ebola is over. Complacency is as dangerous as the Ebola virus itself. ...more]

20 Aug 2015: (Laurie Garrett) Ebola's Lessons: How the WHO mishandled the crisis
https://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/west-africa/2015-08-18/ebola-s-lessons
[This essay by the writer Laurie Garrett will be published in the September/October 2015 issue of Foreign Affairs. She presents a critical retrospective examination of the response to the Ebola outbreak in West Africa. - Mod.LK]

20 Aug 2015: Coal giant exploited Ebola crisis for corporate gain, say health experts
http://www.dailynews.lk/?q=features/coal-giant-exploited-ebola-crisis-corporate-gain-say-health-experts#sthash.cTffrvqc.dpuf
[Public health experts outraged after the world's largest privately-held coal company, Peabody Energy, promotes its product in the fight against Ebola in Africa as part of a PR campaign to rebrand the fossil fuel as a solution to global poverty. Public health experts involved in the response to the Ebola crisis have condemned what they described as a ludicrous, insulting and opportunistic attempt to exploit the disease for corporate gain by the world's largest privately-held coal company. As part of a PR offensive to rebrand coal as a "21st-century fuel" that can help solve global poverty, it has emerged that at the height of Ebola's impact in Africa, Peabody Energy promoted its product as an answer to Africa's devastating public health crisis.

Greg Boyce, the chief executive of Peabody, a US-based multinational with mining interests around the world, included a slide on Ebola and energy in a presentation to a coal industry conference in September last year [2014]. The slide suggested that more energy would have spurred the distribution of a hypothetical Ebola vaccine, citing as supporting evidence a University of Pennsylvania infectious disease expert. The World Health Organisation believes nearly 27 000 people contracted Ebola in an outbreak of the virus in West Africa last year [2014], and more than 11 000 died, although the international agency believes that is probably an underestimate. ...more]

